    Accelerometer -> "Charge Amplifier" -> "Low-pass Filter" -> "Instrumentation Amplifier" -> ADC -> "Digital Processing";

    // Define the anti-aliasing filter as part of the ADC block
    ADC -> "Anti-aliasing Filter" -> ADC;

    // Define that the Digital Processing block outputs to a User Interface or Data Storage
    "Digital Processing" -> "Data Output";
}
```

```Explanations
Accelerometer: A piezoelectric accelerometer converts mechanical vibration into an electrical charge proportional to the acceleration experienced. With a sensitivity of 100 pC/g, it will generate charge according to the vibrations up to 2 Hz and peak amplitude of 5 cm (â‰ˆ0.05g peak acceleration considering simple harmonic motion at 2 Hz).

Charge Amplifier: This block converts the charge output from the piezoelectric sensor into a corresponding voltage. The gain of the charge amplifier will be set to achieve the 1 V peak-to-peak output for the given peak charge from the accelerometer.

Low-pass Filter: The low-pass filter is designed to have a cutoff frequency slightly above the highest frequency of interest (2 Hz) while also ensuring the low-frequency response is 3 dB down at 0.25 Hz. It will attenuate unwanted high-frequency noise and signals beyond the sensor's frequency range, preserving the integrity of the measured signal.

Instrumentation Amplifier: An instrumentation amplifier provides precise, low-noise amplification of the signal from the low-pass filter. Its main function is to increase the amplitude of the signal to a level suitable for analog-to-digital conversion while maintaining a high input impedance and minimizing the effect of offset voltage.

ADC: An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) digitizes the analog signal. Before the actual ADC block, an anti-aliasing filter is employed to prevent aliasing of higher frequency noise or signals into the band of interest.

Anti-aliasing Filter: This filter precedes the ADC to further ensure that any high-frequency signals above the Nyquist frequency are attenuated, preventing them from aliasing into the frequency range of interest during digitization.

Digital Processing: This block represents any digital signal processing required, such as filtering, averaging, or frequency analysis, to interpret the measured vibration signals. It also includes compensation for any offset or drift in the analog circuitry.

Data Output: The final processed vibration data is outputted to a user interface or storage medium. This could be displayed on a screen, stored in memory, or transmitted wirelessly depending on the design of the portable device.
```
